1
00:00:28,306 --> 00:00:31,908
Medford City Council Committee of the Whole, May 26th, 2026 is called to order.

2
00:00:31,948 --> 00:00:33,088
Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

3
00:00:36,290 --> 00:00:36,950
Councilor Kelly?

4
00:00:36,970 --> 00:00:37,050
Aye.

5
00:00:38,951 --> 00:00:39,712
Councilor Lemming?

6
00:00:40,252 --> 00:00:40,632
Present.

7
00:00:43,113 --> 00:00:43,774
Councilor Mullain?

8
00:00:43,794 --> 00:00:45,935
Present.

9
00:00:45,955 --> 00:00:46,715
Councilor Scarpelli?

10
00:00:46,735 --> 00:00:46,875
Present.

11
00:00:48,236 --> 00:00:48,856
Councilor Singh?

12
00:00:48,876 --> 00:00:50,057
Present.

13
00:00:50,077 --> 00:00:50,857
Vice President Lazaro?

14
00:00:50,877 --> 00:00:51,057
Present.

15
00:00:51,878 --> 00:00:52,578
And President Pierce?

16
00:00:52,833 --> 00:00:54,273
Present, seven present, none absent.

17
00:00:54,353 --> 00:00:55,314
Meeting is called to order.

18
00:00:55,934 --> 00:01:00,815
Action and discussion items 26095, submitted by Office of Planning, Development and Sustainability.

19
00:01:01,256 --> 00:01:03,516
Presentation on the Wellington Transformation Study.

20
00:01:03,636 --> 00:01:07,517
And we have our economic development planner, Kayla here with us.

21
00:01:07,577 --> 00:01:12,619
So I will recognize her to introduce the presentation.

22
00:01:15,148 --> 00:01:15,928
Hi, Councillors.

23
00:01:16,768 --> 00:01:24,930
Thank you all for taking the time in this busy season to hear a presentation from our consultants on the Wellington Transformation Study.

24
00:01:25,970 --> 00:01:38,673
The consultant team has an introduction prepared so I won't spend too much time, but just to give you a quick background, the study kicked off in the summer of last year and it considers the future of Wellington here.

25
00:01:39,734 --> 00:01:49,524
the Wellington area in terms of design and connectivity and economic development and how it can grow and change as a neighbourhood.

26
00:01:51,033 --> 00:02:00,862
And we are in the final stages of this study after engagement and outreach and focus groups and a variety of sub-studies that we covered today.

27
00:02:01,602 --> 00:02:13,152
And so today, we ask that as you engage with the presentation, to highlight any points to us that don't sit well or areas where you might have concerns or questions.

28
00:02:15,134 --> 00:02:20,577
And we will use that as input to make the final rounds of edits and revisions.

29
00:02:21,298 --> 00:02:25,641
And what will be produced is a report which will guide future zoning questions.

30
00:02:27,662 --> 00:02:31,825
And so with that said, I will turn it over to agency.

31
00:02:32,665 --> 00:02:39,650
I can introduce Rhiannon, sorry, and Justina and Wallace as the presenters.

32
00:02:45,223 --> 00:02:45,483
Great.

33
00:02:45,543 --> 00:02:46,323
The mic should be on.

34
00:02:47,304 --> 00:02:47,804
Amazing.

35
00:02:47,944 --> 00:02:48,324
Wonderful.

36
00:02:48,404 --> 00:02:49,164
Hi, everyone.

37
00:02:49,765 --> 00:02:50,705
Can you hear me OK?

38
00:02:51,765 --> 00:02:52,226
OK.

39
00:02:52,246 --> 00:02:53,726
All right.

40
00:02:54,206 --> 00:02:54,246
Hi.

41
00:02:54,366 --> 00:02:55,927
My name is Rhiannon Sinclair.

42
00:02:56,687 --> 00:03:00,549
I am a planner with a firm called Agency Landscape and Planning.

43
00:03:00,569 --> 00:03:08,892
And today, I am going to pull up a slide deck on my computer to walk through the Wellington Transformation Study.

44
00:03:08,912 --> 00:03:12,173
So just give me one second.

45
00:03:28,169 --> 00:03:28,890
OK.

46
00:03:29,390 --> 00:03:29,750
All right.

47
00:03:31,891 --> 00:03:33,653
So again, my name is Rhiannon.

48
00:03:33,753 --> 00:03:36,134
I work for a firm called Agency Landscape and Planning.

49
00:03:36,514 --> 00:03:41,978
We had the joy of working on the comprehensive plan together with the city.

50
00:03:42,939 --> 00:03:49,003
We're joined by Innis Associates, who has been doing a lot of zoning work for the city, as well as worked with us on the comprehensive plan.

51
00:03:50,303 --> 00:03:55,327
Bowman Associates, they've done a lot of transportation work in the region, as well as in Medford.

52
00:03:55,667 --> 00:03:57,008
And RKG Associates.

53
00:03:57,929 --> 00:04:02,915
who does a lot of economic development work and will show you a little bit more about what they've done as well.

54
00:04:05,017 --> 00:04:08,422
But first, just to give you a brief overview of this project.

55
00:04:10,685 --> 00:04:28,605
So the Medford Comprehensive Plan articulated as a recommendation that the city should better understand the various neighborhoods that make up the city of Medford and develop more kind of physical and more specific recommendations to guide future change or growth.

56
00:04:29,622 --> 00:04:39,948
And so this project was funded by the Gaming Commission in support of really trying to better understand the impacts of the development of the Encore Casino.

57
00:04:40,568 --> 00:04:53,555
But what it has done is enabled us to think critically about that recommendation from the comprehensive plan to help guide the future of the neighborhood as community needs change, as development happens, and as trends have evolved.

58
00:04:54,455 --> 00:05:11,531
It also means that we've been able to work together with the community, key stakeholders, as well as city leadership to understand what the pain points are in the Wellington neighborhood today and to make decisions or to give you recommendations that help guide you towards change.

59
00:05:12,562 --> 00:05:34,051
And then last but certainly not least, it's a chance to take many studies and a lot of projects and work in this area or places that have impacted this area around land use and zoning, economic development and mobility to ensure that this plan is unified and both connects and supports what is already a thriving neighborhood.

60
00:05:36,322 --> 00:05:54,220
So I'm not gonna go into too much detail around our schedule, but we started this work back in last June, and we've been working over the past year to go about those conversations, to really understand those past studies, and to develop this vision study.

61
00:05:55,041 --> 00:05:59,486
And so what I'm gonna share with you now is effectively a summary draft of that study.

62
00:06:02,057 --> 00:06:12,660
Okay, so that we're all on the same page, the Wellington transformation area that we're looking at doesn't encompass the entire Wellington neighborhood because we're not looking to change everything.

63
00:06:12,780 --> 00:06:27,845
What we're really focused on are the places that are supporting commercial uses today, the places that are supporting transportation uses today that we need to think about now before change happens to them when we don't have the ability to affect that change.

64
00:06:28,845 --> 00:06:39,152
And so this area includes a lot of spaces that either have recently been bought or sold, whether it include the Budweiser Distribution Center.

65
00:06:39,852 --> 00:06:52,140
We have a lot of retail that currently exists in this area, like the Wegmans, Stop and Shop, Aldi, as well as a series of smaller retail and food establishments.

66
00:06:52,860 --> 00:07:06,911
We have Station Landing, which is a more recent development within the area, as well as Wellington Station and a lot of the commercial and residential uses just north of Revere Beach Parkway.

67
00:07:07,631 --> 00:07:18,920
We also, working with Bowman, looked to Mystic Valley Parkway, the Fellows Way, and Revere Beach Parkway to understand where there are opportunities to alleviate some of the pressures on those spaces.

68
00:07:21,487 --> 00:07:28,109
So much of this you likely already know, but here is a brief snapshot of what we understand about Medford as a whole.

69
00:07:29,410 --> 00:07:31,991
You have quite a diverse community.

70
00:07:32,071 --> 00:07:34,732
So one in three residents identify as people of color.

71
00:07:35,212 --> 00:07:39,974
Somerville and Belmont actually have very similar demographic profiles that you have.

72
00:07:40,994 --> 00:07:47,616
You also have a really interesting growing cohort of young professionals, people 25 to 34 who are

73
00:07:50,037 --> 00:08:02,224
who maybe don't want to live directly in the city of Boston, but want to live someplace that they have options to be able to get into the city for work, and to be able to have space or connection to nature close by.

74
00:08:04,405 --> 00:08:09,728
With that surge in 25 to 34 year olds, it also means household size is decreasing.

75
00:08:10,188 --> 00:08:18,113
So there are, you're growing in the number of housing units, the number of people living in each household is going down, and that's for a variety of reasons.

76
00:08:21,022 --> 00:08:27,468
And then last, but certainly not least, you are experiencing a lot of growth in the number of high-earning households.

77
00:08:27,568 --> 00:08:33,314
So people are making a lot more money than they did 10, 20 years ago, even with inflation.

78
00:08:37,225 --> 00:08:52,189
So the key opportunities, and these opportunities have really started to evolve into goals for us, are to encourage growth of the various industry sectors that are unique to Medford, and I'll show you in a moment what some of those industry sectors are that we're looking at.

79
00:08:53,889 --> 00:08:57,650
Places that we think the Wellington neighborhood might be uniquely positioned to support.

80
00:08:58,468 --> 00:09:16,025
We also think this is a really nice moment to lean into what we understand about Medford's residents today and how Medford's resident population is changing by supporting a balance of housing and jobs to create that complete neighborhood that places like Medford Square and other spaces are really already supporting.

81
00:09:17,722 --> 00:09:45,073
We also think this is a really nice moment in every single conversation we had with residents who live here and people who come here on a frequent basis to really think about the, I forget the name, but the rotary at the center of it all oftentimes has a loving name that is labeled in Google Maps as just a really challenging space and a challenge for pedestrians, bicyclists, and cars.

82
00:09:46,494 --> 00:09:56,722
And then last but certainly not least, and this was at the core of pretty much every conversation we had with residents, was this idea of planning or designing for vibrancy and comfort.

83
00:09:56,982 --> 00:10:01,025
People want to have places that feel good.

84
00:10:01,205 --> 00:10:03,227
They want to be in places where they feel included.

85
00:10:03,307 --> 00:10:05,448
They want to have places that are comfortable.

86
00:10:05,589 --> 00:10:13,915
And I think there are many ingredients of that in Wellington, but holding it together is a critical kind of moment for us to be planning for.

87
00:10:17,308 --> 00:10:21,610
So I'm going to briefly walk through some of what the engagement, some of what those conversations included.

88
00:10:22,010 --> 00:10:30,613
We had what are called focus groups or focus conversations with the mayor, with the community development board, who we met with I believe three or four times.

89
00:10:31,513 --> 00:10:36,355
The MBTA, since they have a pretty large amount of holdings within this area.

90
00:10:37,175 --> 00:10:41,877
Various developers who are either actively involved in Medford or looking to be actively involved.

91
00:10:42,818 --> 00:10:50,144
Medford City staff, the public school system, as well as residents who live directly in the neighborhood.

92
00:10:50,184 --> 00:10:56,070
So we had a series of conversations with them, two focus groups and 24 participants.

93
00:10:56,630 --> 00:11:04,818
And then also broader conversations with Medford residents, which included over 50 participants in two open houses.

94
00:11:04,878 --> 00:11:06,980
Those were those kind of science fairs that we had.

95
00:11:07,440 --> 00:11:23,642
And for both the neighborhood resident conversations as well as the broader Medford resident conversations, we took advantage of the city's robocall process to be able to make sure that we're letting people know this is happening so they can opt in or opt out of participating.

96
00:11:25,584 --> 00:11:31,450
What we learned from many of those conversations were that traffic and transportation are pain points.

97
00:11:31,891 --> 00:11:36,055
It's really hard to get around in the neighborhood as well as outside of it.

98
00:11:37,216 --> 00:11:47,447
And it's also, and a lot of residents in the neighborhood shared this, that many different roadways are owned by different entities and that makes it really challenging to manage.

99
00:11:48,919 --> 00:11:57,126
We know, and people talked a lot about how important open space is to them, but we know that open space is abundant.

100
00:11:57,487 --> 00:12:03,973
We also know that those open spaces can be really, really hard to access or to get to.

101
00:12:06,602 --> 00:12:14,446
We learned that other challenges about sewage, water lines, and storm water resulting from development must be mitigated.

102
00:12:14,466 --> 00:12:26,053
While I think city staff really lead in this space, they really care deeply about making sure we can manage water usage and water systems.

103
00:12:26,593 --> 00:12:34,518
It was something that came up a little bit in conversations with residents, too, who are experiencing some of that flooding, which you can see on that bottom left

104
00:12:35,258 --> 00:12:39,679
image, just some of that kind of like daily inland flooding experience.

105
00:12:41,080 --> 00:12:58,045
And then we also learned that parking is definitely a challenge here, especially the challenge of resident versus non-resident parking, so making sure that any investments in more of a destination here support residents first.

106
00:13:00,208 --> 00:13:05,810
So here are just a few images of some of the experiences or challenges that folks articulated.

107
00:13:07,831 --> 00:13:10,672
But people also came to the conversations with a lot of ideas.

108
00:13:12,273 --> 00:13:28,060
There were many conversations about what it means to really embrace the idea of this being a transit-oriented community and providing more housing close to the T as well as, you know, supporting that housing with public realm and open space amenities.

109
00:13:29,882 --> 00:13:41,429
There were many conversations about, and we had a really fun exercise in our second workshop where we asked people to take blocks, building blocks, and actually build what they imagined their city's future land use could be.

110
00:13:41,909 --> 00:13:52,776
A lot of people talked about this idea of adding density and optimizing lots in underutilized areas to support more folks coming in, but also to think about affordability.

111
00:13:54,560 --> 00:14:01,745
There were a lot of opportunities articulated again about transit oriented development as well as connections between neighborhoods and open space.

112
00:14:03,367 --> 00:14:11,935
Some conversations really centered on what is now very much a kind of back of house experience behind a lot of the strip malls.

113
00:14:12,575 --> 00:14:13,676
It's currently a wetland.

114
00:14:13,856 --> 00:14:26,847
It could really be a special moment, but today it is closed off, it's fenced off, but it provides what is a very, very important role in keeping flooding from happening in the Wellington neighborhood.

115
00:14:28,242 --> 00:14:41,514
And then last, again, this idea of vibrant and welcoming that a lot of people would like to see this idea of a kind of supportive community in the neighborhood through better kind of communications of what exists as well as new programming.

116
00:14:44,375 --> 00:14:58,446
And so with all of this feedback that came from residents and came from those focused conversations, we created a vision together with the city's planning group that Wellington is a gateway into the city that Medford is proud of.

117
00:15:01,048 --> 00:15:10,632
That vision also includes this idea that it's a thriving neighborhood with a vibrant and comfortable public realm that people want to be in, and it supports many different experiences for residents and visitors.

118
00:15:11,232 --> 00:15:20,836
And so there were a couple critical pieces to that, one that came from the CD board, this idea of walkable and bikeable mixed-use neighborhoods.

119
00:15:21,797 --> 00:15:31,809
The idea of balancing retail and amenities for residents and neighbors, again, another, you know, it was something that was discussed by residents about how do we think about the tax base and supporting and growing that.

120
00:15:32,610 --> 00:15:35,513
CD board definitely reinforced those points.

121
00:15:37,415 --> 00:15:48,818
We talked about this idea of pairing development with public space, public realm improvements to improve mobility, to expand park space, and to make those spaces high quality.

122
00:15:49,298 --> 00:16:03,502
And then last but certainly not least, let's not continue to build housing that is only one bedroom or studio apartments for the 25 and 34-year-olds, but let's start to build more housing that supports people at many different stages of their lives.

123
00:16:05,962 --> 00:16:26,968
And so briefly, just to touch on the transportation opportunities, we looked to and compared Wellington to a couple different places that are nearby, Central Square in Cambridge, Assembly Square in Somerville, and then Medford Square here in Medford, and started to articulate what it would look like to take

124
00:16:27,588 --> 00:16:41,509
what is now a very, very large block size in Wellington and make that block size a little bit smaller to support some of what makes or what can make a more pleasant experience to walk or to bike or to get around.

125
00:16:43,110 --> 00:16:52,721
And so we also paired that with a better, kind of like deeper understanding of where people currently use vehicles today versus not.

126
00:16:53,642 --> 00:17:00,150
As you can see, Assembly Square, about 50% of people who live in Assembly Square don't use vehicles to get around.

127
00:17:02,833 --> 00:17:10,657
But when you look to west of Wellington Circle, about 20% of people do not use a vehicle to get around.

128
00:17:10,837 --> 00:17:24,564
And then east of Wellington Circle, so again, that really centered space where you have a lot of people living close to the T, many more people are using public transportation because it's close by, because they don't have to cross over the circle to get to those transportation options.

129
00:17:29,687 --> 00:17:29,927
Oops.

130
00:17:31,388 --> 00:17:31,668
Okay.

131
00:17:32,905 --> 00:17:36,629
And so adding more blocks adds more intersections.

132
00:17:37,149 --> 00:17:39,011
Why would we add more intersections?

133
00:17:39,091 --> 00:17:41,093
Intersections can be a problem, right?

134
00:17:42,174 --> 00:17:46,459
Shorter blocks, clearer street hierarchy can mean more options for getting around.

135
00:17:48,869 --> 00:18:18,696
Yes, keeping blocks larger does enable people to move through more quickly, especially in a car, but when you create these kind of smaller moments internal to that large street infrastructure, you create more spaces for people to stop and stay, you have more opportunities to connect buses and to connect vehicles to their destinations, and then you also reduce the amount of energy and the amount of volume that has to be on those bigger streets by distributing that across smaller streets.

136
00:18:21,959 --> 00:18:23,200
All right, so the market analysis.

137
00:18:23,220 --> 00:18:39,714
This is my favorite section, because it digs into a lot of what is going to drive what could happen here in the short term, and what might need to be a longer term investment, and then things that we used to think might be possible here, but maybe are no longer a future for us.

138
00:18:40,830 --> 00:18:46,854
And so the current reality of Medford, and I shared this at the very beginning, is that home prices are quite high.

139
00:18:47,954 --> 00:18:54,638
There are fewer homes for sale in the city of Medford, there are very high interest rates nationally, and it's reduced turnover.

140
00:18:54,918 --> 00:18:56,939
It's made it really difficult for people to buy a house.

141
00:18:57,720 --> 00:19:02,042
Home prices actually are much higher in the region and have grown at a higher pace.

142
00:19:02,743 --> 00:19:06,405
So Medford is experiencing this really big boom in cost for housing.

143
00:19:07,729 --> 00:19:13,497
Simultaneously with high home prices, you're experiencing a lot of actual kind of strong job access.

144
00:19:13,517 --> 00:19:19,145
So you have, Medford has healthcare and education sectors that have been stable.

145
00:19:20,609 --> 00:19:21,330
They're strong.

146
00:19:21,790 --> 00:19:26,656
They aren't necessarily growing at a big pace, but they're staying as they are.

147
00:19:26,676 --> 00:19:30,279
And then other sectors are experiencing slower growth.

148
00:19:30,340 --> 00:19:37,187
So that table or that chart on the right-hand side shows you four quadrants, strong but declining.

149
00:19:37,247 --> 00:19:41,131
You really don't have many job sectors that are declining in Medford.

150
00:19:41,972 --> 00:19:44,875
But you do have a lot in the green that's strong and advancing.

151
00:19:45,676 --> 00:19:54,166
So those educational services, healthcare, social assistance, retail, trade, construction, information, professional services, and tech services.

152
00:19:54,907 --> 00:19:58,691
And then that bottom left, weak and declining.

153
00:19:59,452 --> 00:20:14,344
more of the kind of blue-collar types of jobs like manufacturing, wholesale trade, as well as more kind of white-collar jobs that are declining kind of across the board nationally.

154
00:20:14,724 --> 00:20:20,969
Finance and insurance, real estate services, more admin and support services, those are also declining.

155
00:20:21,650 --> 00:20:24,672
And then accommodation and food services, it's kind of in the center.

156
00:20:24,692 --> 00:20:28,315
It's not growing, but it's not weakening either.

157
00:20:29,640 --> 00:20:33,081
What else has happened is there is a cooled life sciences market.

158
00:20:33,161 --> 00:20:35,702
So the lab market expanded really, really fast.

159
00:20:35,842 --> 00:20:39,603
Everyone wanted to be part of it in the 2010s, into the 2020s.

160
00:20:39,763 --> 00:20:41,964
It expanded too quickly.

161
00:20:42,284 --> 00:20:48,766
There are many labs that are currently sitting vacant, empty in the city of Somerville, in the city of Cambridge.

162
00:20:51,302 --> 00:20:52,902
you know, both good and bad.

163
00:20:52,983 --> 00:20:59,444
Medford was able to kind of miss a lot of that because you weren't quite ready for the lab market.

164
00:20:59,765 --> 00:21:07,927
And that means that this is a really nice moment to reestablish a new hub to think about what types of investments are right for Medford and what will be growing.

165
00:21:10,608 --> 00:21:10,788
So,

166
00:21:12,598 --> 00:21:14,319
What do we see as the near-term possibilities?

167
00:21:14,779 --> 00:21:17,300
There is strong demand for multifamily rental.

168
00:21:17,540 --> 00:21:18,321
That will continue.

169
00:21:18,421 --> 00:21:24,944
People cannot afford to buy houses, interest rates are too high, and so rental housing is the way to go.

170
00:21:26,585 --> 00:21:28,366
We know, too, that the office market

171
00:21:28,786 --> 00:21:34,129
which a lot of what is north of Revere Beach Parkway is currently office commercial.

172
00:21:34,489 --> 00:21:37,210
The office market has more space than what tenants need.

173
00:21:37,590 --> 00:21:46,955
It is making it easier to be a tenant because you can ask for lower per square footage costs, but it also means that the office market is cooling down.

174
00:21:47,155 --> 00:21:49,817
It's not really a space that a lot of folks are creating.

175
00:21:50,737 --> 00:21:58,463
And there's also, what's interesting is this is pretty specific to Medford, there's a stable retail market despite economic uncertainty.

176
00:21:58,683 --> 00:22:04,047
And a lot of that has to do with the audience that lives here and the change in the audience that lives here.

177
00:22:04,327 --> 00:22:13,914
You have younger folks who have a lot of disposable income, they might not have children, and they have higher incomes than what many folks who used to live here have.

178
00:22:14,014 --> 00:22:19,258
So you have a stable retail market that could, there is a chance to grow that.

179
00:22:20,276 --> 00:22:21,077
at least in the near term.

180
00:22:21,677 --> 00:22:39,467
So then in the long term, a possibility there is that rental demand will likely stay high, especially if ownership continues to be limited, and depending on what we see from the kind of like national trend and federal government, what will happen there will dictate where we go with rental versus ownership.

181
00:22:40,854 --> 00:22:54,183
What's interesting is that the industrial market will continue to remain in demand, and the industrial market is large and captures a lot of different things, including things like distribution, but that is an in-demand space.

182
00:22:54,243 --> 00:23:00,067
It will continue to be in demand, especially as redevelopment in cities happens to create more housing.

183
00:23:01,394 --> 00:23:11,986
Last but certainly not least is Tuftec, which until we did this study, I didn't actually know what Tuftec was, so I'll define it for you all.

184
00:23:14,529 --> 00:23:20,836
Tuftec is essentially companies that are in industries that are making what are called complex physical products.

185
00:23:21,617 --> 00:23:23,018
What is a complex physical product?

186
00:23:23,098 --> 00:23:29,581
It is essentially anything within advanced manufacturing, clean energy, manufacturing of medical devices.

187
00:23:29,961 --> 00:23:37,845
A lot of tough tech is growing because it is a space that requires both research and development as well as that initial product development stage.

188
00:23:38,606 --> 00:23:42,048
So tough tech is growing and they really just need

189
00:23:42,768 --> 00:23:46,392
kind of more flexible spaces to be able to make that happen.

190
00:23:46,452 --> 00:23:47,934
So they don't really ask for a lot.

191
00:23:47,954 --> 00:23:51,457
They don't need the lab spaces that life sciences needed.

192
00:23:51,758 --> 00:23:52,979
They really need shells.

193
00:23:55,982 --> 00:24:01,368
And so that's what we're, when we think about what is on the planning horizon, what's on the market horizon, that's what we're looking to.

194
00:24:02,790 --> 00:24:04,552
So when we plan for tomorrow,

195
00:24:05,347 --> 00:24:16,347
We have three future scenarios, I'm gonna go through those scenarios and then I'm gonna share a little bit more about how we consider the kind of market demands against what you want to invest in.

196
00:24:18,563 --> 00:24:25,028
So Wellington today is an interesting, strong commercial, strong industrial defined area.

197
00:24:25,809 --> 00:24:30,012
This identity doesn't exist in many other places within Medford.

198
00:24:30,813 --> 00:24:32,994
So you have about 44% residential, 35% commercial, and 21% industrial.

199
00:24:37,396 --> 00:24:41,740
They are really concentrated in sectors where we see limited growth happening.

200
00:24:41,900 --> 00:24:45,303
And so Medford as a whole might be strong in certain sectors.

201
00:24:45,544 --> 00:24:53,271
Wellington itself has an opportunity to reconnect to and reconsider the sectors that it decides to invest in.

202
00:24:55,280 --> 00:25:10,816
And so we looked at three potential futures, the first being this idea of a commercial center, so digging into, leaning into the near-term possibility of retail demand, while also simultaneously considering the future of industry and tough tech and housing.

203
00:25:11,537 --> 00:25:19,839
The second that we looked at was an industrial node, so repurposing commercial spaces for light industrial use, plus creating some space for mixed-use housing.

204
00:25:20,300 --> 00:25:22,460
And then the last one was, let's go all in on housing.

205
00:25:22,540 --> 00:25:28,522
Let's go all in on the near-term opportunity to build housing where it's needed most.

206
00:25:30,907 --> 00:25:48,049
And so the one that a lot of folks in many of our conversations really landed on or really connected to was the commercial center because it gave us the strength of the near-term possibilities while simultaneously setting ourselves up for a strong long-term future.

207
00:25:49,051 --> 00:25:53,637
And so this is a little bit about what, this is just a kind of initial mapping of what that could look like.

208
00:25:54,599 --> 00:26:02,170
Essentially, you know, really leaning into preserving industrial spaces where those industrial spaces and zones occur.

209
00:26:03,652 --> 00:26:27,769
preserving some critical commercial uses, like the site where you have the Wegmans and other uses there, while also considering new mixed-use development and a little bit more density on the site that currently holds some more strip mall developments, but really protects and turns the wetland space into more of a destination.

210
00:26:29,156 --> 00:26:50,542
And then also simultaneously thinking about north of Revere Beach Parkway as part of the neighborhood fabric, part of the housing fabric that already exists and turning a lot of that over into housing and then bringing more housing close to the T since we know so many people who live close to the T already take advantage of the T and won't be contributing a lot in terms of vehicle use.

211
00:26:52,700 --> 00:27:17,844
And so one example of that, if you've ever been to Watertown's Arsenal Yards recently, it's a really interesting example of that adaptive reuse of buildings that already exist while simultaneously creating mixed-use new development that complements what's there, but also stepping up away from the neighborhood so it doesn't feel like a kind of big, big challenging space.

212
00:27:23,882 --> 00:27:25,694
So I wanna talk a little bit more about...

213
00:27:27,462 --> 00:27:32,424
What does that mean for the types of investments that we're making?

214
00:27:33,025 --> 00:27:42,849
I think that this is something that you all understand quite well, but we've used this a lot in our conversations with the public about how cities bring in and how they spend money.

215
00:27:44,070 --> 00:27:54,115
So cities bring in money through things like local taxes, fees, and other payments, and they spend money by providing municipal services for residents like public safety, education, public works governance.

216
00:27:55,055 --> 00:28:16,108
And so this is very simply put, and this doesn't capture all of the ways that you generate money, like grants and like other forms of revenue, but what you can say is revenues to the city minus the costs that the city has to pay out equals the impact, the fiscal impact of development if a development comes online.

217
00:28:16,468 --> 00:28:21,852
If a new investment is made, if it's a police station, it has a different fiscal impact than a housing development.

218
00:28:22,752 --> 00:28:24,553
Same with a grocery store.

219
00:28:24,693 --> 00:28:26,393
Each one has a different fiscal impact.

220
00:28:28,994 --> 00:28:45,978
And so continuing with that simple way of applying fiscal impact, we looked at all of those different land uses that we articulated for that commercial center to better understand which one has the best impact on the city.

221
00:28:47,163 --> 00:29:01,191
And so, again, this is just looking purely at the revenues that each one provides in dollars per acre per year, minus the costs, and then the blue is the net impact.

222
00:29:01,771 --> 00:29:08,855
So, as you can see, you have your single unit, your single detached units are providing the least amount of net impact.

223
00:29:10,785 --> 00:29:12,570
Your townhomes are providing a little bit more.

224
00:29:12,590 --> 00:29:18,167
Your condos are providing significantly more because you have a lot of density in one space.

225
00:29:19,570 --> 00:29:21,050
Multifamily is a little bit lower.

226
00:29:21,931 --> 00:29:25,291
And then when you enter into, so housing provides some net impact.

227
00:29:25,371 --> 00:29:42,495
When you look at things like office, life science, industrial, or retail, that's where you have significantly higher net impact on the city because those spaces aren't taking advantage of city services in the same way that housing is.

228
00:29:43,518 --> 00:29:49,703
However, these impacts are entirely based on full occupancy and use.

229
00:29:50,384 --> 00:29:57,069
And so what we know is things like life science, there isn't the demand for that.

230
00:29:57,309 --> 00:30:04,955
So anything that you invest in, any life science opportunities, will be challenging to commit to, challenging to be able to have full occupancy of.

231
00:30:05,436 --> 00:30:12,942
And so while it does provide a very large amount of net positive impact, it's currently not feasible in this environment.

232
00:30:14,322 --> 00:30:38,416
So what we did was we took that net fiscal impact and the least feasible, or sorry, the lowest impact is on the left-hand side, the highest impact is on the right-hand side, and then market feasibility, same thing, the least feasible from a market perspective from that, you know, what near-term versus what long-term can this support versus more feasible, we mapped that in a different way to say,

233
00:30:38,836 --> 00:30:46,859
It's not just about what provides the most money to the city, but what will actually commit that money to the city now and in the future.

234
00:30:47,299 --> 00:30:54,462
And as you can see, the things that provide the highest net fiscal impact aren't always the things that are the most market feasible.

235
00:30:55,442 --> 00:31:06,528
But there are places like in industrial uses, retail uses, and market family rental that could provide more of that positive net fiscal impact on the city.

236
00:31:07,608 --> 00:31:15,312
And I think I also want to caveat this with just a really important point, which is that you should never go all in on one thing.

237
00:31:15,633 --> 00:31:20,175
This is always a moment to think about all of these in an ecosystem or a neighborhood condition.

238
00:31:24,556 --> 00:31:38,520
And so last but certainly not least, we've shared with you a little bit about kind of how we got to this idea of a commercial node, and then what does it mean from a kind of fiscal impact market feasibility perspective.

239
00:31:40,001 --> 00:31:41,761
There's also the point about design guidance.

240
00:31:41,821 --> 00:31:51,484
So it's really, really critical that if you are going to transform this neighborhood, that we commit to a series of recommendations about how this neighborhood will look and feel.

241
00:31:52,024 --> 00:32:01,879
People have already said they want it to be vibrant and comfortable and so a few of what we've shared and what we will include in our report will identify some of the ways the city can help get there.

242
00:32:02,480 --> 00:32:07,848
So design guidance is that description of the look feel and quality of a neighborhood.

243
00:32:09,152 --> 00:32:22,481
It is meant to respond to what people want to see there, how they get to school, how they get to work, how they gather, to ensure that it's creating spaces that people feel safe and welcome regardless of the way that they're moving around.

244
00:32:23,322 --> 00:32:31,007
So design guidance is not required by zoning, and it's really meant to be suggestions to support movement forward.

245
00:32:31,567 --> 00:32:46,417
But it can be a really important carrot when you're in conversations with future developers, when you are advocating for the future of this wonderful city to ensure that we are fitting any investments into the existing community fabric and transforming this neighborhood.

246
00:32:47,919 --> 00:32:55,324
And as you can see on the bottom page, these are just a few photos from, you know, getting around the Wellington neighborhood.

247
00:32:55,804 --> 00:32:58,526
There are variable experiences today.

248
00:33:01,098 --> 00:33:10,766
And so the way that the design guidance section of this report will be organized is around four different topics.

249
00:33:10,946 --> 00:33:13,968
The first is this idea of transitions.

250
00:33:13,988 --> 00:33:25,057
So it's really important that when we do consider future development, that we consider building heights that transition up away from the neighborhood, that support

251
00:33:26,298 --> 00:33:41,308
the amount of development that needs to happen for those projects to pencil out while simultaneously protecting the sunlight needs and character and look and feel that the people who live there or work there currently enjoy.

252
00:33:42,725 --> 00:34:00,472
The second is this idea of connectivity and access, being really thoughtful about all of the ways that people can move around, whether they're walking, rolling, or driving, that we're making sure that there are those protected spaces for those things to occur, because today, that is where much of the conflict exists.

253
00:34:02,078 --> 00:34:05,099
Third is to really think critically about neighborhood resilience.

254
00:34:05,399 --> 00:34:06,960
The wetland can do a lot of that.

255
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:10,262
It can act as a sponge park, which will be so, so critical.

256
00:34:10,362 --> 00:34:27,189
If you've ever been to the development north of Alewife Station, really great example of these series of boardwalks that connect into the Minuteman Trail while simultaneously acting as kind of a sponge to collect rainwater and to protect those developments from flooding.

257
00:34:28,009 --> 00:34:31,331
But to encourage that neighborhood-wide resilience both

258
00:34:32,071 --> 00:34:34,912
through water, but also through energy is really important.

259
00:34:35,212 --> 00:34:37,253
And then the last one, prioritizing vibrancy.

260
00:34:37,293 --> 00:34:50,098
And so making decisions about block sizes, creating spaces that are only for pedestrians will make this, will really set this place apart and create a place that everyone can be excited about.

261
00:34:52,925 --> 00:34:56,927
And so I've gone through a lot in a relatively short period of time.

262
00:34:57,387 --> 00:34:59,569
So I welcome any questions that you might have.

263
00:34:59,709 --> 00:35:03,411
Happy to revisit any slides and talk about any of them.

